SIMPLE: flexure
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flexure
<hw>Flex"ure</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>flexura</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of flexing or
bending; a turning or curving; flexion; hence, obsequious bowing or
bending.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Will it give place to <qex>flexure</qex> and low bending?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A turn; a bend; a fold; a curve.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Varying with the <qex>flexures</qex> of the valley through which
it meandered.</q> <rj><qau>British Quart. Rev.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The last joint, or bend, of the
wing of a bird.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>The small distortion of an
astronomical instrument caused by the weight of its parts; the amount to
be added or substracted from the observed readings of the instrument to
correct them for this distortion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The flexure of a curve</b></col> <fld>(Math.)</fld>,
<cd>the bending of a curve towards or from a straight
line.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flibbergib</ent>⟦br⟧
